1060–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1110–1135":"1110–1135","1136–Female":"1136–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","0995–Male":"0995–Deceased","0997–Female":"0997–Deceased","1099":"1099","1110":"1110","1066":"1066","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","0997":"0997","1016":"1016","0995":"0995","1159":"1159","1136":"1136","1025":"1025","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1100":"1100","about 1121":"about 1121","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Evreaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Devereux  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Devereux","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Sean.","English and Irish: of Norman origin, a habitational name for someone from Évreux in Eure, France, with the preposition <i>d(e)</i>. See also   Everest   for the name without the preposition.","History: This was the surname of the Earls of Essex from 1572 to 1641. Walter <i>Devereux</i>, 1st Earl of Essex, led an attempted colonization of Ulster, and his son, Robert, 2nd Earl of Essex, briefly held the position of lord lieutenant of Ireland in 1599."]}]},{"name":"Ala","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Alfred ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":10,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705180,"age":13,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705181,"age":32,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":63,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":83,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":93,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":103,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ala d'Evreaux was born in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England as the daughter of Edward de Évreaux and Maude FitzHubert. She married Elias de Giffard in 1099, in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1121, in her hometown."},"et":{"–about 1121":"–umbes 1121","–1121":"–1121","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1110–1135":"1110–1135","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","0997–Female":"0997–Surnud","1099":"1099","1110":"1110","1066":"1066","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","0997":"0997","1016":"1016","0995":"0995","1159":"1159","1136":"1136","1025":"1025","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1100":"1100","about 1121":"umbes 1121","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–about 1121":"–noin 1121","–1121":"–1121","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1110–1135":"1110–1135","1136–Female":"1136–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","0997–Female":"0997–Kuollut","1099":"1099","1110":"1110","1066":"1066","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","0997":"0997","1016":"1016","0995":"0995","1159":"1159","1136":"1136","1025":"1025","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1100":"1100","about 1121":"noin 1121","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"–about 1121":"–environ 1121","–1121":"–1121","10